 could overtake<ref name="India US Russia World Economy"/><ref name="Economic Order International">{{cite web|title=The West and the Rest in the International Economic Order|url=http://oecdobserver.org/news/archivestory.php/aid/884/The_West_and_the_Rest_in_the_International_Economic_Order.html|work=[[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]]|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref name="2050 Word Economy">{{cite news|title=China, India to Overtake U.S. Economy by 2050|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2017-02-07/china-india-to-overtake-us-economy-by-2050|publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> the [[economy of the United States]] and [[economy of China]] as the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|largest national economy in the world]],<ref name="Hindu">{{cite news|title=Of Oxford, economics, empire, and freedom|newspaper=The Hindu|url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/07/10/stories/2005071002301000.htm|location=Chennai|date=2 October 2005|accessdate=2010-12-06}}</ref> a position [[Economic history of India|it held]]<ref name="British India">{{cite book | title = An Era of Darkness: The British Empire in India| publisher=Aleph Book Company| isbn =978-9383064656 }}</ref> from 1 to 1500 A.D. and in 1700 A.D.<ref>http://glavkonstruktor.ru/upload/img/ADFQtcg.png</ref><ref>Data Source: Tables of Prof. Angus Maddison (2010). The per capita GDP over various years and population data can be downloaded in a spreadsheet from [http://www.ggdc.net/maddison/oriindex.htm here].</ref>
India has created [[North–South Transport Corridor]] as an alternative to [[One Belt, One Road]] policy initiative of China (PRC),<ref name="India TIR">{{cite web|title=India ratifies TIR Convention to access transnational multi-modal connectivity|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/dqvNmMJGbqQAC8pYZPAYdI/India-ratifies-TIR-Convention-to-access-transnational-multi.html|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="India Silk Road">{{cite web|title=Watch Out, China: India Is Building A 'New Silk Road' Of Its Own|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/wadeshepard/2017/06/28/watch-out-china-india-is-building-a-new-silk-road-of-its-own/#515c8a5a90ec|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="India OBOR Counter">{{cite web|title=PM Modi in Russia: How fastracking North-South corridor will help India counter Chinese OBOR|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/pm-modi-in-russia-how-fastracking-north-south-corridor-will-help-india-counter-chinese-obor/696639/|work=[[The Financial Express (India)]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> to link in with Iran, Russia, the Caucasus, and Central Asia. In 2017, India and [[Japan]]<ref name="India Japan AAGC">{{cite web|title=India And Japan Join Forces To Counter China And Build Their Own New Silk Road|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/wadeshepard/2017/07/31/india-and-japan-join-forces-to-counter-china-and-build-their-own-new-silk-road/#2fb1ae0b4982|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="India Japan AAGC2">{{cite web|title=Ignoring OBOR, India and Japan forge ahead with joint connectivity project|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ignoring-obor-india-and-japan-forge-ahead-with-joint-connectivity-project/articleshow/59830218.cms|work=[[The Economic Times]]|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> joined together to form [[Asia-Africa Growth Corridor]], to better integrate the economies of South, Southeast, and East Asia with Oceania and Africa.<ref name="India Japan AAGC"/><ref name="India Japan AAGC2"/>
